Q. 1293. shortest-path-in-a-grid-with-obstacles-elimination

Things to remember:
1. In normal BFS, we only track position in queue, Deque<int[]> with i,j
2. If we have obstacles, we track the state as follows: Deque<int[]> with i,j,k where k: remaining count 
3. Important point, if Deque tracks state using three variables, visited must also track all three variables

Variant 1: For normal BFS, we mark the visited=3 in the grid itself.
Variant 2: For normal BFS, we mark the visited=true in another boolean grid.

We can do the same for obstacle problem as well, mark visited separately.
Changing input grid is never permitted, if we have to keep track of such obstacle state.

Even if we manage to track visited separately, the core problem of this Q.1293 is different.
There can be two valid path that reaches an obstacle and we cannot mark an obstacle as visited.
Each of these paths can have a different value of k and can work differently around that obstacle.

Changing input grid - NO
Tracking visited separately - Also, NO [Cant distinguish between "visited with k=0 remaining" and "visited with k=1 remaining]
Tracking visited separately WITH obstacle count - YES (same state variables as the queue)


In standard BFS:
  State = (row, col)
  Visited = boolean[R][C]
  Same cell visited twice = redundant, block it

In constrained BFS:
  State = (row, col, k)
  Visited = boolean[R][C][k+1]
  Same cell visited twice WITH SAME K = redundant, block it
  Same cell visited twice WITH DIFFERENT K = different state, allow it
  k is part of input variable state, overriding the input matrix can cause issues.
  What about walls and gates? => 
  Yes, we mark grid values as visited. Even when there are obstacles.
    The FIRST time BFS reaches any cell is ALWAYS the minimum distance.
    Therefore writing that distance and blocking future visits is correct.
    Second visit would only bring equal or larger distance — useless.


  But, if it had constraints on obstacle removal - it will work same as Obstacle elimination
  You can no longer use the grid value as visited marker because the same cell can be reached with different k values — exactly the same reason as Obstacles Elimination.  
  Why this guarantee BREAKS when you add obstacle removal:
  With k obstacle removals, two paths can reach the same cell with the same distance but different k remaining


Grid-as-visited = safe when state has NO extra dimensions
Separate visited array = required when state has ANY extra dimensions

Shortcut check: count your state tuple dimensions
(row, col)      → 2D state → grid marking safe
(row, col, k)   → 3D state → need boolean[R][C][k+1]
(row, col, k, t)→ 4D state → need boolean[R][C][k+1][t+1]

The grid marking trick is an optimization that only works for the simplest case. The moment your problem adds any constraint that changes what you can do from a position — that optimization breaks and you need the full visited array.
